<div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />You could replace the internal RAM with a 8K SRAM if you wanted to and had homebrew that would utilize it. It might break a game if it relies on RAM being mirrored. But you could install switches to fix this. But since it's easier to just put RAM in the cartridge that makes more sense.<br /></div><br />The gameboy actually had a full 8kb of internal ram. As a result, it was easier to make complex games with large maps and lots of dynamic objects. One potential drawback is that programmers no longer needed to be clever and efficient with their ram utilization. A benefit obviously would be that the cartridges would be cheaper, since they would rarely need to contain extra ram, unless you want battery-backed sram.<br /><br />However, the gameboy came out 4 years after the NES, so Nintendo could put more ram in the units and still have them be affordable, thanks to Moore's law.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=21">Drag</a> — Fri Jun 24, 2011 2:01 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
